    value: 꽃소식을 알려주는 바람이라는 24차례의 화신풍(花信風) 중 가장 나중에 부는 바람인 연화풍(楝花風)을 가리킨다. 3월 곡우(穀雨) 이후 세 번째로 부는 바람으로, 절후로는 늦봄에 해당한다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 납향(臘享) 고사 : '
    value: 사제(蜡祭)는 납향(臘享) 제사라는 말인데, 연말(年末)에 올리는 감사(感謝)와 기원(祈願)을 위한 제(祭)이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 䲧 : '
    value: 塢
english:
  title: Twelve Songs of Farm Life
  author: Seo Hyo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Moon

    Spring flings wide the reins of sky,
    soaring free through vast expanse.
    Pond waters shimmer, ice cracks apart,
    warm winds bend the willows gold.
    With striped staff the farmer drives his ox,
    turning fields to start the year's great work.
    Sun's warmth quickles smartweed sprouts,
    snow-melted chickweed spreads on sunny slopes.
    All the village spreads their wine cups out,
    seek the moon through Lantern Festival night,
    the moon rises heartless, shining down,
    yet old men read its fortune every year.

    Second Moon

    Alfalfa shoots, mugwort still stands short,
    doors close tight till weather warms.
    The granary in town keeps back spring grain,
    ten thousand mouths cry out for lack.
    This spring let barley know no delay,
    yet seed runs short and hands lack work.
    Between the clouds, dawn sun strikes the fields,
    jade scales shimmer, iron plows flash bright.
    Spring's messenger sends word down the line,
    the scholar tree blooms gold.

    Third Moon

    The cuckoo cries, new swallows dance,
    a hundred feet of gossamer hang from high trees.
    Twenty-four times the flower-wind blows,
    one gust, then two, brings soft-falling rain.
    When weather smiles, the farmer's work grows urgent,
    yet none bring wine to seek the spring meadow.
    Village headmen call through barren towns,
    apricot blossoms spread, sweet flag leaves thicken.
    Farm work scatters everywhere,
    ten thousand hands hold hoe and spade, thick as clouds.

    Fourth Moon

    All flowers fall, spring's labor ends,
    the sky clears, orioles' songs flow smooth.
    Young pheasants nest in marshland reeds,
    village folk hunt fern on mountain slopes.
    Silkworms sleep piled high, hearts roasted,
    ten acres dark with mulberry dense.
    Fields crack open, algae clots form,
    they go spy springs, pull water wheels.
    Silkworms need drought, crops need rain,
    heaven's mind remains unclear—which side to aid?

    Fifth Moon

    Midsummer now, all things flourish thick,
    elm and willow villages see daylight lengthened.
    Back lane pomegranates bloom above short fences,
    front neighbor's young bamboo shades the path.
    Green waves across the rise turn dusky gold,
    in every home the mortar pounds sweet cakes.
    Swing ropes hung in lanes when Dragon Boat comes,
    ramie skirts flutter, scatter, gather again.
    Fields of seedlings stretch like cloudy green,
    dove-wives cry for rain with urgent voice.

    Sixth Moon

    The sun at noon could melt ten thousand pearls,
    old farmer labors, weeding hundred plots.
    From field-head songs are answered at field's end,
    the east side done, now westward comes the turn.
    After eating, rest on brick beneath grass,
    dark tree-shade holds fragrant wind aplenty.
    Fragrant wind turns to mountain rain,
    white waves ripple till no earth shows through.
    Riding home, the ox beneath them backward,
    reed-pipe's note—the day grows dim.

    Seventh Moon

    When rains collect and heat retreats at last,
    cicadas chirp the coming autumn's tongue.
    By east fence, jade-green melons split open,
    small crocks ferment new grain to wine.
    Neighbors share their cups along the path,
    drunken singing "ahhh," hands linked, feet stumbling.
    Farm's half-labor finished now,
    let hoe-ends shed their caked mud clean.
    Meeting, talking, dusk creeps near,
    dew descends on autumn rice heads.

    Eighth Moon

    White dew falls in silence, grass grows thin,
    in every cottage, red dates picked ripe.
    Swallows leave their nests, wild geese send word,
    all things grow meager, autumn deepens.
    Rice plants shift from green to amber gold,
    field-colors fade to ruddy cloud-light.
    At the dam's head, silver fish flex fins,
    beneath the reeds, purple crabs bear roe.
    Free from labor, food enough to eat,
    old and young alike sing songs of peace.

    Ninth Moon

    Rapeseed greens emerge, taro roots grow fat,
    frost arrives, the farm-folk dress anew.
    Sparrows peck the late-fall ground,
    when harvest time comes, clouds grow dark.
    Dagger at the waist, pushing cart up slopes,
    this hill strips grain, that house goes home.
    Chrysanthemums bloom round the thatched cottage,
    music, drums ring out across all fields.
    White wine by the measure, one chicken brought,
    together they make autumn offering to sacred grove.

    Tenth Moon

    Good month arrives, earth and heaven hush,
    all harvested crops stacked high as houses.
    Cold nights echo with the pounding stone,
    steamed cakes rise white with fragrant steam.
    Rich folk pay light taxes, granaries full,
    poor folk pay rent and still fall short.
    Both rich and poor know worry, joy alike,
    difference lies in mere inches of belly.
    Striving hard to fill the mouth,
    yet must still prepare new cotton robes.

    Eleventh Moon

    Days grow short as winter solstice nears, stars bright,
    whirlwinds shake the night through heaven and earth.
    Before year's end, three snows have fallen white,
    ten days of seeping moisture soaks the young wheat.
    Warm earth-warmth glows from hearth-fire,
    slant sun beyond the hills sends pheasants flying.
    In the pot beans simmer soft as cream,
    smoke rises lonely from the cold woods' edge.
    Driving ox to manger, feeding bean husks,
    the tax-collector comes knocking at the door.

    Twelfth Moon

    Clouds blanket fields in murky cold,
    both north and southern hills turn crystalline.
    Gathered by the hearth, folk shrink like turtles,
    deep in snow-paths through the woods—how one longs for warmth.
    The elder checks old contracts, wife counts spun thread,
    paper windows glow dim with oil-lamp light.
    Hawks hunt rabbits, catching winter's blessing,
    the year-end sacrifice brings wine and meat.
    Welcoming the new, we fear the old returns,
    we plead with earth's lord—grant us favorable answer.
  footnotes:
    - The 'flower-wind' (花信風) referenced in Third Moon is one of twenty-four seasonal winds in traditional East Asian meteorology, each associated with blossoming flowers. The particular wind mentioned here marks the transition to late spring.
    - The 'year-end sacrifice' (臘享) in Twelfth Moon is an ancient ritual of thanksgiving and supplication performed at year's close to honor the gods and seek blessings for the coming year.
